<!-- ━━━ CHAPTER 5: Five Capabilities ━━━ -->
<section class="slide slide--lifecycle" id="lifecycle">
  <div class="wrap" style="width: min(95%, 90rem)">
    <p class="section-label reveal">Chapter 5</p>
    <h2 class="section-title reveal reveal-delay-1">The Complete Lifecycle</h2>
    <p class="text-muted reveal reveal-delay-1" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-s); color: var(--text-faint); font-size: 0.9rem;">Click any capability to explore</p>

    <div class="lifecycle-container reveal reveal-delay-2">
      <div class="lifecycle-wheel-wrap">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 500 500" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" id="lifecycleWheel">
          <!-- Connector lines from center to nodes (drawn by JS) -->
          <g id="connectorLines"></g>

          <!-- Dashed arc connectors -->
          <g id="arcs" stroke-dasharray="6 4" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.3">
          </g>

          <!-- Center hub (static, no spin) -->
          <g id="lifecycleHub">
            <circle cx="250" cy="250" r="58" fill="oklch(95% 0.008 55)" stroke="oklch(88% 0.008 55)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="250" y="242" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Outfit, sans-serif" font-weight="700" font-size="15" fill="oklch(18% 0.01 55)">Vault PKI</text>
            <text x="250" y="258" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans, sans-serif" font-size="11" fill="oklch(45% 0.01 55)">+</text>
            <text x="250" y="274" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Outfit, sans-serif" font-weight="700" font-size="15" fill="oklch(18% 0.01 55)">AAP</text>
          </g>

          <!-- Nodes will be created by JS -->
        </svg>
      </div>

      <div class="lifecycle-detail">
        <div class="lifecycle-detail-panel active" data-cap="issue">
          <div class="capability-number">01 / 05</div>
          <h3 style="color: #0F62FE;">Issue &amp; Deploy</h3>
          <p>Vault's PKI engine generates short-lived X.509 certificates with policy-enforced common names, TTLs, and key usage constraints. AAP deploys them to target services with validated configuration and automatic service reload.</p>
          <ul style="--dot-color: #0F62FE;">
            <li>Dynamic issuance — certificates generated on demand, not pre-provisioned</li>
            <li>Policy-as-code — CN restrictions, TTL limits, key types all enforced by Vault</li>
            <li>Service-aware deployment — nginx gets PEM files, Tomcat gets PKCS12 keystores</li>
            <li>TLS verification — handshake confirmed before marking deployment complete</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="lifecycle-detail-panel" data-cap="monitor">
          <div class="capability-number">02 / 05</div>
          <h3 style="color: #009D9A;">Monitor</h3>
          <p>Continuous certificate expiry tracking across every host in the fleet. Configurable thresholds trigger renewal workflows before certificates approach expiry — shifting from reactive firefighting to proactive management.</p>
          <ul style="--dot-color: #009D9A;">
            <li>Fleet-wide visibility — know the status of every certificate at any time</li>
            <li>Configurable thresholds — default 30 days, adjustable per environment</li>
            <li>Compliance-ready reporting — audit your certificate posture on demand</li>
            <li>Read-only — safe to schedule daily without risk of changes</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="lifecycle-detail-panel" data-cap="renew">
          <div class="capability-number">03 / 05</div>
          <h3 style="color: #198038;">Renew</h3>
          <p>When certificates approach their expiry threshold, AAP automatically issues replacements from Vault, backs up the existing certificate, deploys the new one, and verifies the TLS handshake — all without human intervention.</p>
          <ul style="--dot-color: #198038;">
            <li>Conditional — only renews hosts that actually need it</li>
            <li>Backup-first — existing certificate preserved before replacement</li>
            <li>Verified — TLS handshake confirmed after every renewal</li>
            <li>Schedulable — run daily at 2 AM, forget about it</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="lifecycle-detail-panel" data-cap="revoke">
          <div class="capability-number">04 / 05</div>
          <h3 style="color: #DA1E28;">Revoke</h3>
          <p>When a certificate is compromised or needs to be invalidated, security teams can revoke it instantly through Vault's PKI engine. CRL updates propagate automatically. Revocation is always a deliberate security decision — never automated.</p>
          <ul style="--dot-color: #DA1E28;">
            <li>Instant — revocation takes effect in Vault immediately</li>
            <li>Intentional — never triggered automatically by rollback or failure</li>
            <li>Audited — every revocation recorded with timestamp and operator</li>
            <li>CRL management — optional tidy operation cleans up expired entries</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="lifecycle-detail-panel" data-cap="rollback">
          <div class="capability-number">05 / 05</div>
          <h3 style="color: #B28600;">Rollback</h3>
          <p>If a new certificate causes service issues, AAP restores the previous certificate from a timestamped backup, reloads the service, and verifies recovery — automatically during deployment, or manually when needed.</p>
          <ul style="--dot-color: #B28600;">
            <li>Automatic — triggered by block/rescue if deployment or verification fails</li>
            <li>Manual option — run the rollback playbook for emergency recovery</li>
            <li>Latest backup auto-detected — or specify a specific backup path</li>
            <li>Verified — TLS handshake confirmed after rollback completes</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

